On February 9, 2018, the President signed into law the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2018. This act includes several provisions related to budget and spending. Division B of the enrolled bill provides emergency supplemental appropriations for recent disasters, as well as tax relief and Medicaid changes. It also includes a short-term continuing resolution that provides appropriations for the Federal Government until March 23, 2018. Division C increases the defense and non-defense category caps for FY 2018 and FY 2019, extends the sequestration of mandatory spending by two years, and establishes two Joint Select Committees to improve multiemployer pension plans and reform the budget process. It also suspends the statutory debt limit until March 1, 2019. Division D extends tax relief provisions for families and individuals, as well as incentives for job growth and energy production. Division E extends or modifies various health programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, and includes offsets related to these programs. Division F includes agriculture program improvements for cotton, livestock, and dairy producers. Division G provides direction regarding the budgetary effects of the other divisions. More information on these provisions can be found in the attachment.